message.content:
We start by extracting the ending balances from the statements and then compute each ratio step‐by‐step.

1. Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
 • Operating cash flow (from cash flow statement): 116257.19  
 • Total current liabilities (from balance sheet): 967271.87  
  Ratio = 116257.19 / 967271.87 ≈ 0.12

2. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 • Total Liabilities = Total Liabilities and Owner’s Equity – Owner’s Equity  
  = 14930535.06 – 13963263.19 = 967271.87  
 • Owner’s Equity = 13963263.19  
  Ratio = 967271.87 / 13963263.19 ≈ 0.07

3. Total Asset Turnover Ratio  
 • Main Business Revenue (or Total Revenue) = 3025437.82  
 • Total Assets (end balance) = 14930535.06  
  Ratio = 3025437.82 / 14930535.06 ≈ 0.20

4. Quick Ratio  
 Quick assets include Cash on Hand, Bank Deposits, Interest Receivable and Accounts Receivable (but exclude Inventory).  
 • Cash on Hand = 3537257.19  
 • Bank Deposits = 4579000.00  
 • Interest Receivable = 14869.76  
 • Accounts Receivable = 1716911.17  
  Sum of quick assets = 3537257.19 + 4579000.00 + 14869.76 + 1716911.17 = 9848038.12  
 • Quick Ratio = 9848038.12 / 967271.87 ≈ 10.17

5. Operating Cash Flow Ratio  
 This uses the same values as in (1).  
  Ratio = 116257.19 / 967271.87 ≈ 0.12

6. Return on Equity (ROE)  
 • Net Profit = 963263.19  
 • Owner’s Equity = 13963263.19  
  ROE = 963263.19 / 13963263.19 ≈ 0.069 or 6.90%

7. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
 • Revenue = 3025437.82  
 • Accounts Receivable = 1716911.17  
  Ratio = 3025437.82 / 1716911.17 ≈ 1.76

Putting it all together, we have:

    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "0.12",
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.07",
    "Total Asset Turnover Ratio": "0.20",
    "Quick Ratio": "10.17",
    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "0.12",
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "6.90%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "1.76"
  }
}
